@page "/"

<h3>MEV Validation Demo — Blazor Web App</h3>
<p>
    This app tests the <strong>MEV (Microsoft.Extensions.Validation)</strong> source-gen code path
    in <code>DataAnnotationsValidator</code>. When <code>AddValidation()</code> is called and a
    model has <code>[ValidatableType]</code>, the <code>DataAnnotationsValidator</code> uses
    <code>TryValidateTypeInfoAsync</code> → <code>IValidatableInfo.ValidateAsync</code> →
    <code>asyncAttr.GetValidationResultAsync()</code> instead of the fallback
    <code>Validator.TryValidateObjectAsync()</code>.
</p>

<div class="alert alert-primary">
    <strong>Key insight:</strong> The <strong>only</strong> difference between MEV and fallback pages
    is whether the model has <code>[ValidatableType]</code>. Both use
    <code>&lt;DataAnnotationsValidator /&gt;</code> and the same async validation attributes from
    <code>SharedModels</code>. The <code>DataAnnotationsValidator</code> auto-selects the code path.
</div>

<h4>MEV Path (source-gen)</h4>
<div class="list-group mb-3">
    <a href="/mev-registration" class="list-group-item list-group-item-action list-group-item-primary">
        <strong>MEV Registration:</strong> <code>MevUserRegistration</code> with
        <code>[ValidatableType]</code> — <code>[UniqueUsername]</code>, <code>[UniqueEmail]</code>
        validated via <code>GetValidationResultAsync()</code>
    </a>
    <a href="/mev-order" class="list-group-item list-group-item-action list-group-item-primary">
        <strong>MEV Order:</strong> <code>MevOrder</code> with <code>[ValidatableType]</code> —
        <code>[AsyncProductExists]</code> + <code>IAsyncValidatableObject</code> via MEV pipeline
    </a>
</div>

<h4>Fallback Path (runtime Validator)</h4>
<div class="list-group mb-3">
    <a href="/fallback-registration" class="list-group-item list-group-item-action list-group-item-secondary">
        <strong>Fallback Registration:</strong> <code>SharedModels.UserRegistration</code> (no
